    <!-- Definition: pivot position / pivot column -->
    <definition xml:id="def-pivot">
      <title>Definition: Pivot Position and Pivot Column</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <em>pivot position</em> in a matrix <m>A</m> is a location in <m>A</m> that corresponds to a leading <m>1</m> in the RREF of <m>A</m>.
          A <em>pivot column</em> is a column of <m>A</m> that contains a pivot position.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <!-- Guided computation: RREF and pivot columns -->
    <task xml:id="task-pivots" workspace="true">
      <title>Compute RREF and Identify Pivot Columns</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Express the matrix in RREF and identify the pivot columns.</p>
        <p>
          <m>
            \left[
            \begin{array}{rrrr}
            0 \amp -3 \amp -6 \amp 4 \\
            -1 \amp -2 \amp -1 \amp 3 \\
            -2 \amp -3 \amp 0 \amp 3
            \end{array}
            \right]
          </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <!-- Algorithm: Row reduction -->
    <paragraphs xml:id="algo-rref">
      <title>Row Reduction Algorithm (Steps to RREF)</title>
      <p>The algorithm below produces a matrix in RREF.</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Step 1a:</strong> Swap the first row with a lower one so the leftmost nonzero entry is in the first row.</li>
        <li><strong>Step 1b:</strong> Scale the first row so that its leading entry equals <m>1</m>.</li>
        <li><strong>Step 1c:</strong> Use row replacement so all entries below this <m>1</m> are <m>0</m>.</li>
        <li><strong>Step 2a:</strong> Swap the second row with a lower one so the leftmost nonzero entry below the first row is in the second row.</li>
        <li><strong>Continue:</strong> Repeat to obtain echelon form with leading entries equal to <m>1</m>.</li>
        <li><strong>Last step:</strong> Use row replacement so all entries above each leading entry are <m>0</m>, starting from the right.</li>
      </ol>
    </paragraphs>

    <!-- Example: basic and free variables -->
    <example xml:id="ex-basic-free">
      <title>Basic and Free Variables</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Consider the augmented matrix <m>\left[\,A\,\middle|\,\vec b\,\right]</m>:</p>
        <p>
          <m>
            \left[
            \begin{array}{ccccc|c}
            1 \amp 3 \amp 0 \amp 7 \amp 0 \amp 4 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 4 \amp 0 \amp 5 \\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 6
            \end{array}
            \right]
          </m>
        </p>
        <p>
          The leading ones are in the first, third, and fifth columns. Thus, the pivot variables of the system
          <m>A\,\vec x \,=\, \vec b</m> are <m>x_1</m>, <m>x_3</m>, and <m>x_5</m>; the free variables are <m>x_2</m> and <m>x_4</m>.
          <em>Any choice</em> of the free variables leads to a solution of the system.
        </p>
        <p><em>Note:</em> The matrix <m>A</m> itself does not have “variables”; systems have variables.</p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <!-- Theorem: existence and uniqueness -->
    <theorem xml:id="thm-existence-uniqueness">
      <title>Theorem: Existence and Uniqueness of Solutions</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A linear system is consistent iff the last column of the <strong>augmented</strong> matrix does not have a pivot.
          Equivalently, the RREF of the augmented matrix does <em>not</em> contain a row of the form
          <m>\left[\,0,\,0,\,0,\,\dots,\,0 \,\middle|\, 1\,\right]</m>.
        </p>
        <p>If a linear system is consistent, then:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>It has a unique solution iff there are no free variables.</li>
          <li>Otherwise, it has infinitely many solutions parameterized by the free variables.</li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

